Introduction

Dataset Description

This data set contains information about 10,000 movies collected from The Movie Database (TMDb), including user ratings and revenue. Using numpy and pandas I will perfom analysis and try to get some insights on how some data affect others over the years.

We have two datasets that we will combine later to have one full dataset. The first is movie tmdb_5000_movies.csv and has 4803 rows 20 columns. The second dataset will use is tmdb_5000_credits.csv that has 4803 rows 4 columns. Certain columns, like cast and genres, 'production_company', production_country, 'keywords', 'spoken_language' and 'crew' contain multiple values that are arrays of dictionaries.

List all column names in each table, and their significance. In case of multiple tables, describe the relationship between tables.

Question(s) for Analysis

  1. Which year produced more movies
  2. Which genre has made more movies?
  3. What are the most profitable genres?
  4. Which movies have The movie with the Highest and Lowest Profit and Revenue?
  5. How does the budget affect the profit??
  6. Which are the top 10 movies that have The movie with the Highest Revenue?
  7. How does the budget affect the vote average?
  8. What are the Top Actors by number of movies?
  9. How does the Popularity affected the profit over the years?
  10. Which countries produce more movies?
  11. How does the Run time relate to the vote average?

Overview of the Datasets

TMDB 5000 Credits

Shape: 4803 rows 4 columns

Columns:
  • movie_id (int64): Unique identifier for each movie.
  • title (object): Title of the movie.
  • cast (object): information about the cast.
  • crew (object): information about the crew.

TMDB 5000 Movies

Shape: 4803 rows 20 columns

Columns:
  • budget (int64): Budget of the movie.
  • genres (object): Genres of the movie.
  • homepage (object): URL of the movies homepage.
  • id (int64): Unique identifier for each movie.
  • keywords (object): Keywords.
  • original_language (object): Original language of the movie.
  • original_title (object): Original title of the movie.
  • overview (object): Brief description of the movie.
  • popularity (float64): Popularity score.
  • production_companies (object): Production companies.
  • production_countries (object): Production countries.
  • release_date (object): Release date of the movie.
  • revenue (int64): Revenue generated by the movie.
  • runtime (float64): Duration of the movie.
  • spoken_languages (object): Spoken languages.
  • status (object): Release status of the movie.
  • tagline (object): Tagline of the movie.
  • title (object): Title of the movie.
  • vote_average (float64): Average voting score.
  • vote_count (int64): Number of votes received.

# Let's  extract name and gender from the cast
def extract_cast_info(x):
    return [[i['name'], i['gender']] for i in x]

# This extracts name, job, department, and gender from the crew
def extract_crew_info(x):
    return [[i['name'], i['job'], i['department'], i['gender']] for i in x]

# Apply the extraction functions to the parsed columns
df['cast'] = df['cast'].apply(extract_cast_info)
df['crew'] = df['crew'].apply(extract_crew_info)

Research Question 3 What are the most profitable genres

In[187]:
#we have to find the profit first
df['profit'] = df['revenue'] - df['budget']

# Extract genre names
df['genre_names'] = df['genres'].apply(lambda x: [genre['name'] for genre in x] if isinstance(x, list) else [x['name']] if isinstance(x, dict) else x)

# Explode the genre names
genre_profit = df.explode('genre_names').groupby('genre_names')['profit'].mean().sort_values(ascending=False)

plt.figure(figsize=(16, 8))
genre_profit.plot(kind='bar')
plt.title('Average Profit by Genre')
plt.xlabel('Genre')
plt.ylabel('Average Profit')
plt.xticks(rotation=45, ha='right')
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

This graphy shows us the average profit by genre. Animation, Adventure and Fantasy make more profit

Research Question 4 Which movies have The movie with the Highest and Lowest Profit and Revenue?

In[188]:
#This function helps us to get hold of columns and find the highest and lowest indexes in a column and display the columns dynamically.
def calc_min_max(column):
    #getting the lowest in the column
    min = df[column].idxmin()
    #getting the maximum value in the column
    high = df[column].idxmax()
    highest = pd.DataFrame(df.loc[high,:])
    lowest = pd.DataFrame(df.loc[min,:])
    #printing the results
    print(df['original_title'][high] + ' has the highest ' +  column + ' and ' + df['original_title'][min] + ' has the lowest ' +  column)
    #concanitanting our two columns
    return pd.concat([highest,lowest],axis = 1)

Research Question 8 What are the Top Actors by number of movies?

In[195]:
from collections import Counter

# Flatten the cast list
all_actors = [actor for movie_cast in df['cast'] for actor in movie_cast]

# Count appearances
actor_counts = Counter(actor[0] for actor in all_actors)

# Get top 10 actors
top_10_actors = actor_counts.most_common(10)

# Visualize
plt.figure(figsize=(16, 8))
sns.barplot(x=[actor[0] for actor in top_10_actors], y=[actor[1] for actor in top_10_actors])
plt.title('Top 10 Actors by Number of Movies')
plt.xlabel('Actor')
plt.ylabel('Number of Movies')
plt.xticks(rotation=45, ha='right')
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Samuel L. Jackson, Robert De Niro and Bruce Willis made more movies than other actors.

Research Question 9 How does the Popularity affected the profit over the years?

In[196]:
yearly_data = df.groupby('year')[['popularity', 'profit']].mean()

plt.figure(figsize=(16, 8))
plt.plot(yearly_data.index, yearly_data['popularity'], label='Popularity')
plt.plot(yearly_data.index, yearly_data['profit'] / 1e6, label='Profit (millions)')
plt.title('Average Popularity and Profit by Year')
plt.xlabel('Year')
plt.ylabel('Value')
plt.legend()
plt.show()

Both popularity and profit lines show significant fluctuations over the years, indicating a volatile industry or market.

Research Question 10 Which countries produce more movies?

In[197]:
# First, we need to extract and count the production countries
from collections import Counter

all_countries = [country['name'] for countries in df['production_countries'] for country in countries]
country_counts = Counter(all_countries)

# Get top 10 countries
top_10_countries = dict(country_counts.most_common(10))

plt.figure(figsize=(16, 8))
plt.bar(top_10_countries.keys(), top_10_countries.values())
plt.title('Top 10 Movie Production Countries')
plt.xlabel('Country')
plt.ylabel('Number of Movies')
plt.xticks(rotation=45, ha='right')
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

US and UK produce more movies
